<subSubSection lastPageId="92" lastPageNumber="92" pageId="91" pageNumber="91" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="91.[701,1228,915,1759]" pageId="91" pageNumber="91">
COMMENTS: Rothschild apparently had the single specimen of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rothschild" authorityYear="1896" box="[992,1110,1094,1115]" class="Aves" family="Cnemophilidae" genus="Loboparadisea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="91" pageNumber="91" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sericea">
<emphasis box="[992,1110,1094,1115]" italics="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="91">L. sericea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
when he described both the genus and species as new. 
<bibRefCitation author="Rothschild" box="[701,992,1151,1174]" firstAuthor="Rothschild" page="169" pageId="91" pageNumber="91" pagination="169" refId="ref134152" refString="Rothschild, W. 1897 e. On the figures on Plate II. Novitates Zoologicae 4: 169, pl. II." type="journal article" year="1897" yearSuffix="e">Rothschild (1897e: 169)</bibRefCitation>
believed ‘‘Koeroedoe’’ to be on the north coast of Dutch New 
<collectingCountry box="[701,790,1210,1232]" name="Guinea-Bissau" pageId="91" pageNumber="91">Guinea</collectingCountry>
. Kurudu Island is in fact at the mouth of the Mamberamo River and specimens from there were thought to come from mountains south of the Mamberamo. 
<bibRefCitation author="Hartert" firstAuthor="Hartert" page="127" pageId="91" pageNumber="91" pagination="123 - 178" refId="ref125804" refString="Hartert, E. 1919. Types of birds in the Tring Museum. B. Types in the general collection. Novitates Zoologicae 26: 123 - 178." type="journal article" year="1919">Hartert (1919: 127)</bibRefCitation>
discussed the uncertainty associated with the collecting locality of this 
<typeStatus box="[1170,1223,1357,1378]" pageId="91" pageNumber="91">type</typeStatus>
, saying that collectors for van Renesse van Duivenbode, from whom Rothschild purchased the specimen, had bought it from residents of Kurudu Island. Later (
<bibRefCitation author="Stresemann" firstAuthor="Stresemann" page="145 - 146" pageId="91" pageNumber="91" pagination="144 - 147" refId="ref137685" refString="Stresemann, E. 1934. Vier neue Unterarten von Paradiesvogeln. Ornithologische Monatsberichte 42: 144 - 147." type="journal article" year="1934">Stresemann, 1934: 145–146</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Hartert" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Hartert" page="167" pageId="91" pageNumber="91" pagination="165 - 240" refId="ref126298" refString="Hartert, E., K. Paludan, Lord Rothschild, and E. Stresemann. 1936. Die Vogel des Weyland- Gebirges und seines Vorlandes. Mitteilungen aus dem Zoologisches Museum in Berlin 21: 165 - 240." type="journal article" year="1936">Hartert et al., 1936: 167</bibRefCitation>
, fn. 2) it became clear that van Renesse van Duivenbode (from whom had come a number of specimens with confusing collecting localities) had collectors working in the Weyland Mountains.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="91.[701,1228,915,1759]" lastBlockId="92.[93,619,213,264]" lastPageId="92" lastPageNumber="92" pageId="91" pageNumber="91">
<bibRefCitation author="Cracraft" box="[731,942,1679,1701]" firstAuthor="Cracraft" page="6" pageId="91" pageNumber="91" pagination="1 - 43" refId="ref121493" refString="Cracraft, J. 1992. The species of the birds-ofparadise (Paradisaeidae): applying the phylogenetic species concept to a complex pattern of diversification. Cladistics 8: 1 - 43." type="journal article" year="1992">Cracraft (1992: 6)</bibRefCitation>
considered 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rothschild" authorityYear="1896" class="Aves" family="Cnemophilidae" genus="Loboparadisea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="91" pageNumber="91" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="91">Loboparadisea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to comprise two phylogenetic species, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rothschild" authorityYear="1896" class="Aves" family="Cnemophilidae" genus="Loboparadisea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="91" pageNumber="91" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sericea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="91">L. sericea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[838,946,1738,1759]" class="Aves" family="Cnemophilidae" genus="Loboparadisea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="91" pageNumber="91" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aurora">
<emphasis box="[838,946,1738,1759]" italics="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="91">L. aurora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but other authors have recognized a single biological species with two subspecies.
</paragraph>
